.SH expand, unexpand â€” expand tabs to spaces, and vice versa

.SH USAGE
expand [-t tablist] [file ...]

unexpand [-a] [file ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
expand processes the named files or the standard input, writing the standard output with tabs changed into blanks.
Backspace characters are preserved into the output and decrement the column count for tab calculations.
expand is useful for pre-processing character files (before sorting, looking at specific columns, etc.) that contain tabs.

unexpand puts tabs back into the data from the standard input or the named files and writes the result on the standard output.

.SH OPTIONS

-t tablist: tabs are set tablist spaces apart instead of the default 8. If multiple -t options are given, then the tabs are set at those specific columns.

.SH EXIT STATUS
The expand and unexpand utilities exit 0 on success, and >0 if an error occurs.
